column271: I began by investing 100% of my funds in Asset A. Then  I pretty much put 50% in Asset B and 50% in Asset A. This was my strategy for all 3 parts. I understood everything completely.

I made my investment decision based primarily on the previous years' outcome. If the interest rate for the previous year was very low  I would select Asset A which was uncertain but had a chance of gaining higher returns. I would select Asset B  which was a fixed interest rate  only after the interest rate for the previous period was high for Asset A. After trying it out in the practice runs  I decided not to purchase the 4% chance of winning $20 as the compounded probability of winning the $20 was very low and not worth it as it would result in a net loss in the long run. |  | This experiment went by smoothly and was clear and easy to understand.

I didn't like the uncertainty of the experiment  especially since there was no real strategy that went along with it. It was all based on luck and perception of what was going to happen. Part way through the first part of the experiment  I ddecided that I should go 100% in for asset A for the rest of the experiment because it was more beneficial that I risk everything. If the multipler for asset A happened to be between 1.00 to 1.10ish  then my payout if I chose 50% A and 50% B would be 1.5*1.10  which wouldn't be as high as 3*1.10. If the multipler was less than 1.00  I knew I would lose money  but I had faith that I would somehow regain the money back. During a path  if I had gain a lot of money during a period  I would try to save as much as possible just in case if the multiplier for asset A was significantly small. I would try to invest aroudn $3-$5 depending on how much I earned the pervious period.

I believe I understood everything about the experiment... my strategy was to start off with a very low percentage invested in Asset B  in hopes of getting a high investment back on Asset A.  Once my sum started growing  I became more cautious with how I split the Assets  and gave more and more to Asset B as it's a confirmed growth investment.  Once Asset C was introduced  as long as my sum was around $7 or higher  I bought into it.  Then no matter how low my sum was  as long as I had at least $1.50 in Period 10 I would buy Asset C  because at that point $1 wasn't going to make much of a difference towards my final sum  but in the event that I got the $20 it would make a big difference. |  | Note: I'm not an international student  but I wrote Israel as my home state/country as I went to high school in Israel.  I'm American and have always been in an American/International school system  but the last time I actually lived in the US was elementary school.

I would generally start out with a 2:1 b to a ratio  then generally keep that until the 4th or 5th move  then drop the ratio to nearly all a in hopes for a high payoff. If it did not work  I would take it back to the previous ratio. There was a lot of guesswork generally. Also  if the amount ever got above twenty dollars or so  I would raise the ratio to all b  thus eliminating all risk of losing money. I would try to avoid investing in b when the multiplier was less than one  but in many cases it was unavoidable.
It.s not fair to random select the payment. It should be the average or the median of all the earnings. | The investment decision is somewhat like stock or gambling. It really needs good luck.

The decision I made was depended on the multiplier of previous period. It is more likely to be higher multiplier if the previous periods kept being low. The asset c is not likely to win and I just took chance when my payoff is high  and 1 dollar does not make big different. Moreover  I only pay attention to the average income of others in part 3.

I set rules for myself  like a lot of people do playing Blackjack. I would envest fully in Asset A when under $10  because the difference between potentially earning $2 or $8 for me is somewhat negligible. But the potential to instead earn $100 due to a high factor outcome on A was worth the risk. Once I was over $15  I'd always set my investment in asset B to a minimum of $15 for safety. Anytime my total was over $15  I'd also put money toward Asset C  despite how much it is in favor of the system. Although the strategy was "riskier"  there wasn't much at risk. |  | Everything was clear and approachable. However  the needed step of pressing % or $ at the start of each path seems unneccesary. I would have preferred it just default to % or $.
Always invested a good amount in Asset A first period and based my decisions on if there were consecutive low returns the periods before

In the first subset  I was very cautious. In the 2nd and 3rd I was much more liberal with my money  always investing a large percentage on the first period. If I lost money from Asset A  then I would usually invest even more in it the next time. Investing in the possible $20 never seemed worthwhile so I didn't do that.
